<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=0 WIDTH="95%"><TR ><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#F0DCA0" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Axe</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">unpolished.<P>as i said before, positive comments are very nice and all, but they lead nowhere. and as i also said, if i didnt like the game over all i wouldnt even post about it.<P>so! there we are after playing alot of hours with it. the game interface gives me the impression of a (great... yes. sadly.) lack of polish. i find myself thinking "this could be better" and actually finding HOW it could be better quite a bit too often to my liking. <P>things like dubious clicking accuracy, backed up by overpowered (and undocumented) features such as a attack nearest target key, lack (in my opinion) of ease of using pieces of equipments, items and such, choosing spells, backed up by a pause function that breaks all the flow of the game. lack of letting us know when we have an item on drag and a very chaotic inventory system... makes me feel like i want more.<P>when i look at the refined graphics, awesomely composed, beautifully played and very well interwined soundtrack (i mean that. its one of the best soundtracks for a game i ever heard.) intricate plot, the game NOT taking us for fools to the point of walking us by the hand trough quests, very good quality of all animations and graphics, and im skipping some stuff... <P>i feel like im reading a very good book on pages scattered on the floor, or that im watching a dvd on a 1070's black and white TV set. <P>the contrast between the overall game quality and the intuitiveness and basic workings of the user interface is so great that it gives the whole game a bitter taste.<P>as much The Lord Of The Rings deserves to be written on quality paper, as much as Schindler's List deserves to be played on a good tv set, Divine Divinity needs a better user interface.<P>kick your game from played to lived.</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Arhu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hi Axe!<P>~<I>i find myself thinking "this could be better" and actually finding HOW it could be better quite a bit too often to my liking</I>~<P>Then you should not only say what's lacking or not good, but also state HOW you'd like it to be or what you think could be improved.  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><BR>Things like that can be adressed in patches, although it's of course better if that wasn't necessary. Besides, this <I>is</I> still a demo after all, and demos are often not a glimse <I>of</I> the final game but a glimse <I>at</I> what the final game might look like.<P>That said, the word goes on to the developers.  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P><I>Meow...</I><BR>Arhu</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">lar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Err... I can follow you on some things to a certain extent, but on some I can't:<P>Things like dubious clicking accuracy: I'm not even going to bother commenting on this one anymore - I'll just put the two systems in, and everyone can judge for themselves that an environment where you can interact with a lot of objects does not work with the traditional system of per pixel accuracy. Case closed  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P>Attack nearest target key <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/biggrin.gif">on't agree, it's not overpowered.<P>lack (in my opinion) of ease of using pieces of equipments:Can you elaborate on this ?<P>Backed up by a pause function that breaks all the flow of the game <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/biggrin.gif">on't agree, in my opinion it adds a lot to the game.<P>Lack of letting us know when we have an item on drag:Errr...this one I don't get. You see the object in your mouse cursor, don't you ?<P>A very chaotic inventory system:That's been adjusted since the demo I believe in that items are ordered better.<P>Lar</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Moriendor</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by lar:<BR><I>.<P>lack (in my opinion) of ease of using pieces of equipments:Can you elaborate on this ?<BR></I><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Hehe, I could so let me help Axe a bit here  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"> .<BR>It isn't too comfortable when you're dealing with two separate windows and have to drag'n'drop equipment from one to the other. Merging the equipment and inventory windows into a single window would have helped a lot. May be a matter of taste but I also have a strong preference for inventory slots. The inventory is really pretty chaotic but you said it has improved so there's hope  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"> .<BR>Another thing that is pretty confusing is that you have to drag items from your inventory on top of other items in the world. Most gamers are probably used to picking items up and then combining them in the inventory window.<BR>You get quickly used to the inventory/equipment management in  <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/div.gif"> but when someone is saying you "have to get used to something" it usually indicates there's something wrong  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"> . Luckily, there's not much wrong in Divinity's case  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"> .<P>------------------<BR>Moriendor<BR>Editor @ <A HREF="http://www.rpgdot.com/" TARGET=_blank>RPGDot</A><BR>Webmaster @ <A HREF="http://ww